<paragraph id="666036ACFFA8FFA9BDF2B99716EF8A9B" blockId="95.[151,1436,1190,1447]" pageId="95" pageNumber="96">
<emphasis id="54ABEABEFFA8FFA9BDF2B99715B18A30" box="[207,457,1268,1292]" italics="true" pageId="95" pageNumber="96">Diagnostic characters</emphasis>
: The two broad, large and lobe-like pars ventralis (
<figureCitation id="FEE42A29FFA8FFA9B936B99610EE8A30" box="[1035,1174,1268,1292]" captionStart="FIGURE 33" captionStartId="100.[151,250,1680,1703]" captionTargetBox="[288,1289,164,1665]" captionTargetId="figure-109@100.[240,1374,153,1665]" captionTargetPageId="100" captionText="FIGURE 33. Allocladius spp., male hypopygium; A, D, G, dorsal aspect; B, E, F, pars ventralis; C, F, I, ventral aspect. A–C. A. neobilobulatus (Paggi). D–F. A. globosus Andersen, Saether et Mendes.; G–I. A. quadrus Andersen, Saether et Mendes. (From Andersen et al. 2010.)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5288353" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5288353/files/figure.png" pageId="95" pageNumber="96">Fig. 33 A–C</figureCitation>
) will separate the male imago from all other 
<taxonomicName id="A1DF4D2FFFA8FFA9BCB6B87916518A0F" authorityName="Edwards. This" authorityYear="1932" box="[395,553,1307,1331]" class="Insecta" family="Chironomidae" genus="Pseudosmittia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="95" pageNumber="96" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="54ABEABEFFA8FFA9BCB6B87916518A0F" box="[395,553,1307,1331]" italics="true" pageId="95" pageNumber="96">Pseudosmittia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The acrostichals also are stronger than normal and the accessory lobe of the inferior volsella is barely indicated. The pupa is very similar to that of the Holarctic 
<taxonomicName id="A1DF4D2FFFA8FFA9B95AB82111378A66" authority="(Kieffer)" baseAuthorityName="Kieffer" box="[1127,1359,1346,1370]" class="Insecta" family="Chironomidae" genus="Allocladius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="95" pageNumber="96" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nanseni">
<emphasis id="54ABEABEFFA8FFA9B95AB82110008A66" box="[1127,1144,1347,1370]" italics="true" pageId="95" pageNumber="96">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="54ABEABEFFA8FFA9B9B5B82110A78A66" box="[1160,1247,1347,1370]" italics="true" pageId="95" pageNumber="96">nanseni</emphasis>
(Kieffer)
</taxonomicName>
, but is distinguishable by having a papilla on the genital sac which is nearly twice as long as wide and more numerous spinules on the posterior sternal conjunctives.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="666036ACFFA8FFA9BDAAB8BC105E8ACA" blockId="95.[151,1062,1502,1526]" box="[151,1062,1502,1526]" pageId="95" pageNumber="96">
The male and associated pupa is described in detail in Andersen 
<emphasis id="54ABEABEFFA8FFA9BE56B8BD17DB8ACA" box="[875,931,1502,1526]" italics="true" pageId="95" pageNumber="96">et al.</emphasis>
(2010: 14).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="666036ACFFA8FFA9BDAABB4E15648978" blockId="95.[151,929,1580,1643]" box="[151,284,1580,1604]" pageId="95" pageNumber="96">
